  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining the Project Scope**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a grasp of the task. My focus is on understanding the project\'s parameters. I recognize the objective: designing a website (landing page) for \"Veneza Barbearia\" is critical, and the current payment situation is a clear pain point. I need to make the new payment setup elegant.\n\n\n**Refining the User Flow**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the user journey, influenced by the Own Barber Club website. The key shift? Let\'s begin with location selection (with photos and addresses), *then* display the available plans for that specific unit. The plan details must clearly mark that they are monthly subscriptions and have visuals.\n\n\n**Mapping the Components**\n\nI\'m now outlining the website\'s structure. I\'ll need `LocationSelector` and `PlanViewer` components. The data model includes `locations` (with ID, name, address, image, plan IDs) and `plans` (ID, name, price, features, image, checkout URL). Placeholders for locations will allow user edits. I\'m leveraging public Unsplash images to ensure visual appeal. I\'ve also determined some realistic tiers like \"Basic\", \"VIP\", and \"Premium\" for the barber club plans.\n\n\n**Defining the Visual Style**\n\nI\'m now thinking about the look and feel. The reference site inspires a dark, elegant aesthetic with moody images and typography. For the hero, I envision a dark, moody barber shop image. Location imagery will need exterior/interior shots, with abstract textures or styling photos for the plans, like haircuts. The flow will involve scrolling to a unit selection, leading to plan views, and a \"back to units\" navigation option.\n\n\n**Constructing the Foundation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the implementation details. I\'m building `LocationCard.tsx`, `PlanCard.tsx`, and `App.tsx`, and I\'m using `motion` for smoother transitions and local state for management. I\'m adding Google Fonts to `index.css` (Playfair Display for headings, Inter for body). I also need to rename `metadata.json` to \"Clube Veneza Barbearia.\" I\'m also planning the data structure for locations and plans. I have some sample locations and plans to test with.\n\n\n**Implementing the Framework**\n\nNow I\'m focusing on implementation, with `App.tsx` handling layout and state. I\'ve corrected the client name in the metadata to \"Veneza Barbearia.\" The visual style will be a modern, dark mode, drawing from their branding and Instagram. I\'m executing the tool calls to update `metadata.json`, `index.html`, and `index.css`. Types and data structures are taking shape, and the font links are ready to go.\n\n\n**Defining the Type Structures**\n\nI\'m now nailing down the TypeScript definitions. I\'ve defined the `Location` and `Plan` interfaces to ensure data consistency. The `Location` interface encompasses `id`, `name`, `address`, `imageUrl`, and `planIds`. Meanwhile, the `Plan` interface captures `id`, `name`, `price`, `description`, `features`, `imageUrl`, and `checkoutUrl`. I have also begun adding some sample plans.\n\n\n**Adding Plan Details**\n\nNow I\'m focusing on refining the plan data. I\'ve added more details, including descriptions, features, and checkout URLs for each plan. I\'ve enriched the plan data, including \"Clube Kids\" to expand the offerings. This will allow a more compelling presentation. I\'m also ensuring the data aligns with the overall vision for the site.\n\n\n**Refining the Data Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the data and focusing on the `App.tsx` component, including the smooth scrolling logic, with the initial view being the hero and the locations. I\'m adding `Clube Kids` as a plan with details, and I am also adding new sample plans to the dataset. I also need to refine the location data to match the image URLs.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 57
      nanos: 815827984
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
